            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Koa Santos is a product of the Bay Area\u2019s cultural confluence. Born in Daly City to a Filipino father who served in the U.S. Navy and a Native Hawaiian mother he met while stationed at Pearl Harbor, Koa\u2019s childhood was a warm blend of lively family parties, the scent of chicken adobo, and the gentle strum of a ukulele. His parents instilled in him a powerful sense of *'ohana* and responsibility, expecting him to be a provider and a rock for the family.\n\nHe started a Business Administration degree at San Jose State, the first in his family to attend a four-year university. However, his trajectory shifted abruptly during his sophomore year when his father suffered a major health crisis, forcing him to leave school and find full-time work to help with the sudden influx of medical bills. What was meant to be a temporary pause became a permanent detour. Koa\u2019s natural charisma and calm demeanor landed him a customer service role, which he eventually parlayed into his current position as a Client Relationship Associate for a management consulting firm in SoMa.\n\nNow 28, Koa lives in a small but tidy one-bedroom apartment in the Lower Haight. His days are structured: a quick coffee from a local cafe before hopping on the Muni for the short ride downtown. At work, he excels at managing difficult clients, his inherent patience a key asset. After work, he either hits the gym or tries to perfect his mother\u2019s recipes, filling his apartment with the familiar aromas of home.\n\nA recent breakup with a long-term girlfriend, who was more career-driven, left him feeling adrift and questioning his path. He feels the weight of his unfinished degree, not for the career-advancement, but as a personal milestone left incomplete. His secret dream is to one day save enough to start a food pop-up, \"Mana Meals,\" fusing the Filipino and Hawaiian flavors of his youth. For now, he finds solace in the city's energy\u2014the diverse crowds at Dolores Park, the fog rolling over Twin Peaks, and the feeling of being an integral, quiet part of San Francisco's complex heartbeat, still figuring out how to honor his past while building a future that is entirely his own."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe remembers being twelve, squeezed between aunties on the living room couch in Daly City. The air was thick with the scent of garlic from his dad\u2019s chicken adobo and the sweet sound of his mom\u2019s ukulele. His father\u2019s deep, booming laugh was the rhythm of the party. He felt an overwhelming sense of belonging, a warmth that anchored him. It was the first time he understood *'ohana* wasn\u2019t just about family; it was a feeling, a safe harbor he has carried with him ever since.\n\n2.\nHe was nineteen, sitting in the sterile quiet of the San Jose State library, when his mom called. Her voice, usually so steady, was frayed with panic about his dad. The drive back up the 101 wasn't for a weekend visit; it was a retreat. That night, seeing his father looking so frail, he silently packed his collegiate dreams away. Responsibility had a new, heavier weight, and he shouldered it without a word. It\u2019s a promise he feels he is still keeping.\n\n3.\nAt twenty-five, a senior partner was screaming on speakerphone. While his colleagues shrunk back, Koa calmly listened, his voice never rising above a gentle cadence, just as his mother would when mediating family spats. He de-escalated the crisis, earning a rare nod of respect. In the silence afterward, he realized his greatest professional asset wasn't from a textbook; it was inherited patience. The thought brought a pang of both pride and melancholy. He was using his family\u2019s gift, but not for anything that truly fed his soul.\n\n4.\nIt was six months ago, over dinner at a place she\u2019d chosen. She was mapping out their five-year plan\u2014her promotion, a condo in a shinier neighborhood. When he shyly mentioned his pop-up idea, she called it a \"cute hobby.\" The word landed like a stone. He saw their futures branching away right there at the table; her path a paved highway, his a winding trail he hadn't yet dared to walk. In that moment, he felt profoundly alone, even sitting directly across from her.\n\n5.\nA few weeks ago, sitting alone on the grass at Dolores Park, he watched a patchwork of groups sharing food from different containers\u2014a vibrant, informal potluck. The easy laughter reminded him of his childhood parties. Suddenly, \"Mana Meals\" wasn't just a fantasy; it felt vital. He pictured serving pork longganisa sliders next to lomi-lomi salmon, fusing his parents\u2019 worlds on a paper plate. For the first time since leaving school, a future he *built* felt not just possible, but necessary."
